05033nam a22006735i 9780812298642DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122986427 a10.9783/97808122986422doi  a(DE-B1597)627887  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a306.42231 aCutter, Martha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Many Resurrections of Henry Box Brown /cMartha Cutter. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations for Archives Consulted -- tIntroduction. The Many Resurrections of Henry Box Brown, the Man Who Mailed Himself to Freedom -- tChapter 1. Slavery and Freedom in US Visual Culture -- tChapter 2. Becoming Box Brown, 1815–1857 -- tChapter 3. Performing Fugitivity -- tChapter 4. Performing New Panoramas, Mesmerism, Spiritualism, and Second Sight, England, 1857–1875 -- tChapter 5. Canada, the United States, and Beyond -- tChapter 6. The Absent Presence -- tChapter 7. Playing in the Archives -- tCoda. The Resilience of Box Brown and the Afterlives of Slavery -- tAppendix. Selected Contemporary Creative Works About Henry Box Brown -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn March 23, 1849, Henry Brown climbed into a large wooden postal crate and was mailed from slavery in Richmond, Virginia, to freedom in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. “Box Brown,” as he came to be known after this astounding feat, went on to carve out a career as an abolitionist speaker, actor, magician, hypnotist, and even faith healer, traveling the United States, the United Kingdom, and Canada until his death in 1897.The Many Resurrections of Henry Box Brown is the first book to show how subversive performances were woven into Brown’s entire life, from his early days practicing magic in Virginia while enslaved, to his last shows in Canada and England in the 1890s. It recovers forgotten elements of Brown’s history to illustrate the ways he made himself a spectacle on abolitionist lecture circuits via outlandish performances, and then fell off these circuits and went on to reinvent himself again and again. Brown’s stunts included creating a moving panoramic picture show about his escape; parading through the streets dressed as a “Savage Indian” or “African Prince”; convincing hypnotized individuals that they were sheep who would gobble down raw cabbage; performing magic, dark séances, and ventriloquism; and even climbing back into his “original” box to jump out of it on stage.In this study, Martha J. Cutter analyzes contemporary resurrections of Brown’s persona by leading poets, writers, and visual artists. Both in Brown’s time and in ours, stories were created, invented, and embellished about Brown, continuing to recreate his intriguing, albeit fragmentary and elusive, story. The Many Resurrections of Henry Box Brown fosters a new understanding not only of Brown’s life but of modern Black performance art that provocatively dramatizes the unfinished work of African American freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 4aArts-History of Art. 4aInterdisciplinary-African American Studies. 4aLit Crit-American Literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  aFrederick Douglass.  aSojourner Truth.  aWilliam Ellen Craft.  arespectability politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812298642?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978081229864242